<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF206-946-950  </DOCNO><DOCID>06 946 950.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The New York Times  Jan 18 1989 v138 n47,754 pC1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Putting data at your fingertips. (midget computers for datastorage and retrieval) (includes related article: 'Why spellingmachines sometimes flunk'.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pollack, Andrew.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Advances in memory-chip capacity and in data compression make newproducts possible - handheld dictionaries, spelling checkers,translators, appointment calendars and file systems.andP;  Suchdevices, which are midget computers dedicated to particularpurposes, fill aisles at the Consumer Electronics Show, held inLas Vegas, NV, Jan 7-10, 1989.andP;  There are two main categories:electronic reference works, like spelling checkers; and electronicorganizers, which manage information such as appointments or phonenumbers.andP;  Franklin Computer Corp, which sells products rangingfrom a $50 spelling checker to a $400 dictionary-thesaurus thattalks, will report about $68 million from sales of electroniclanguage products in the fiscal year ending Mar 1989, up from $22million in the preceding year.andP;  Franklin's rival, Selectronics, isalso doing well.andP;  But investors are suspicious, fearing a fad.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Hand-Held ComputersInformation SystemsConsumer Electronics ShowTrendsMemoryData CompressionSpelling CheckersConsumer ElectronicsMarket AnalysisOutlook.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>